div.p: Why not LIMIT/OFFSET? OFFSET N forces the DB to scan and discard N rows O(N) full-index skip scan. Cursor uses (created_at, id) < predicate O(log N) index range scan every time.

ol.li: N+1 Strategy: Detects the end of the collection without an extra DB count.
Composite Cursor: (created_at, id) is required to prevent data skipping if multiple rows share a timestamp.
Index Coverage: Ensure the composite index matches both the WHERE filter and the ORDER BY clause exactly.

div.p: sql SELECT * FROM urls WHERE user_id = $1 ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 20 OFFSET 200;
Problem: DB engine must traverse 220 index entries and discard first 200. Complexity: O(OFFSET)
sql SELECT * FROM urls WHERE user_id = $1 AND (created_at, id) < ( SELECT created_at, id FROM urls WHERE id = $2) ORDER BY created_at DESC, id DESC LIMIT 21;
DB seeks directly to row via index. Complexity: O(log N)
Extract: after (UUID) and limit (int). Validate: Clamp limit [1, 100]. Check UUID format. Null Check: after == "" implies first page.
Execute: repo.List(userID, after, pageSize + 1) Trick: Fetch N+1 rows to check for "HasNext" without COUNT(*).
Seek matches user_id prefix, then traverses tree to (created_at, id) anchor in O(log N) time.
Query Plan: Index Scan Backward on idx_urls... Index Cond: (user_id = $1) AND (created_at, id) < (...) Rows Removed by Filter: 0
sql SELECT ... FROM urls WHERE user_id = $1 ORDER BY created_at DESC, id DESC LIMIT 21
sql SELECT ... FROM urls WHERE user_id = $1 AND (created_at, id) < (subquery) ORDER BY created_at DESC, id DESC LIMIT 21
HasNext: True Action: Trim row 21. Cursor: Row 20's ID.
HasNext: False Action: Keep all rows. Cursor: Nil.
